answer:
The graph of $y = ax^2 + bx + c$ is a parabola.  For $x = 0$ and $x = 1,$ $y = c$ and $y = a + b + c,$ respectively.  So the parabola passes through the points $(0, c)$ and $(1, a + b + c).$

[asy]
unitsize(1 cm);

pair trans;

real f1 (real x) {
  return (-2*x + 2);
}
real f2 (real x) {
  return (2*x);
}
real f3 (real x) {
  return (-4*x^2 + 8*x - 2);
}
real f4 (real x) {
  return (4*x^2 - 8*x + 2);
}
real f5 (real x) {
  return (-8*x^2 + 12*x - 4);
}
real f6 (real x) {
  return (8*x^2 - 12*x + 4);
}

trans = (-2,0);

draw((-3,0)--(5,0),Arrows(6));
draw((0,-5)--(0,5),Arrows(6));

for (int i = -5; i <= 5; ++i) {
  draw((0,i)--(1,i),gray(0.7));
  draw((i,0)--(i,1),gray(0.7));
}

draw(shift(trans)*graph(f1,-1,3),red);
draw(shift(trans)*graph(f2,0,2),red);
draw(shift(trans)*graph(f3,-1,3),red);
draw(shift(trans)*graph(f4,0,2),red);
draw(shift(trans)*graph(f5,0,2),red);
draw(shift(trans)*graph(f6,0,2),red);

label("$y = c$", (-2,0.5) + trans, N);
label("$y = a + b + c$", (1,0.5) + trans, N);
[/asy]

If we want $|a| + |b| + |c|$ to be as large as possible, then we want two of $a,$ $b,$ and $c$ to be equal to 1 or -1.  If the parabola passes through the points $(0, 1)$ and $(1, -1),$ then $c = 1$ and $a + b + c = -1,$ so $a + b = -2.$  Similarly, if the parabola passes through the points $(0, -1)$ and $(1, 1),$ then $c = -1$ and $a + b + c = 1,$ so $a + b = 2.$

If $a + b = 2$ and $c = -1,$ then $|a| + |b| + |c| = |a| + |2 - a| + 1.$  If $a < 0,$ then this expression is equal to $-a + |2 - a| + 1,$ which is at most 3, when $a = -1.$  If $a \ge 0,$ then this expression is equal to $a + |2 - a| + 1,$ which is at most 5, when $a = 2.$

If $a + b = -2$ and $c = 1,$ then $|a| + |b| + |c| = |a| + | -2 - a| + 1.$  If $a < -2,$ then this expression is equal to $-a + | -2 - a| + 1,$ which is at most 3, when $a = -2.$  If $-2 \le a \le 0,$ then this expression is equal to $-a + | -2 - a| + 1,$ which is at most 5, when $a = 0.$

Thus, the largest possible value of $|a| + |b| + |c|$ is $\boxed{5}.$  This can be achieved, for example, with the quadratic $y = 4x^2 - 8x + 2,$ which passes through the points $(0, 2),$ $(1/2, -1),$ and $(1, 2).$

